<header class="header">
      <h1>Seed Starting Schedule for Short Growing Seasons</h1>
      <p class="tagline">
        A clear method for planning indoor starts and transplant timing.
      </p>
      <p class="lede">
        In short growing seasons, timing is constrained by frost at <strong>32°F (0°C)</strong>.
        Because the frost-free window is limited, seed starting schedules should be built
        around your typical last frost date and the usable season length that follows.
      </p>
    </header>

    <section class="card">
      <h2>Start With One Anchor Date</h2>

      <p>
        Every spring plan begins with your <strong>average last frost date</strong> at 32°F.
        This date is based on 1991–2020 climate normals and typically framed at the
        <strong>50% probability</strong> level.
      </p>

      <p>
        That anchor date becomes the reference point for:
      </p>

      <ul>
        <li>Indoor seed starting windows</li>
        <li>Hardening off periods</li>
        <li>Outdoor transplant timing</li>
        <li>Direct sow windows</li>
      </ul>

      <p>
        Find your local frost boundary using the
        <a href="/tools/frost-date-finder/">Frost Date Finder</a>.
      </p>

      <p>
        Instead of guessing when to plant, count backward (or forward) from that climate boundary.
        If you prefer to generate windows automatically, use the
        <a href="/tools/seed-start-planner/">Seed Starting Planner</a>.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="card">
      <h2>The 3 Planning Windows That Matter</h2>

      <h3>1. Indoor Start Window</h3>
      <p>
        Most warm-season crops need a 6–10 week indoor head start in shorter climates.
        Counting backward from your typical last frost date ensures seedlings are ready
        when frost risk historically declines.
      </p>

      <p>
        Starting too early can result in overgrown plants waiting for safe conditions.
        Starting too late reduces the total frost-free season available for development.
      </p>

      <h3>2. Hardening Off Period</h3>
      <p>
        Plan 7–10 days before transplanting to gradually expose seedlings to
        wind, sun, and temperature swings.
      </p>

      <p>
        In short climates, transplant shock can compress the already limited
        heat accumulation window. For a structured approach, see
        <a href="/guides/how-to-harden-off-seedlings/">How to Harden Off Seedlings</a>.
      </p>

      <h3>3. Transplant or Direct Sow Window</h3>
      <p>
        Warm-season crops are typically transplanted after the 32°F frost boundary.
        Cool-season crops may be planted slightly before it depending on tolerance.
      </p>

      <p>
        The objective is to align planting with declining frost risk while maximizing
        remaining seasonal heat accumulation. Estimate seasonal heat using the
        <a href="/tools/growing-degree-day-planner/">Growing Degree Day Planner</a>.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="card">
      <h2>Which Crops Should You Start Indoors?</h2>

      <p><strong>Usually started indoors (short-season advantage):</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li><a href="/crops/tomatoes/">Tomatoes</a></li>
        <li><a href="/crops/peppers/">Peppers</a></li>
        <li>Broccoli</li>
        <li>Cabbage</li>
        <li>Kale</li>
      </ul>

      <p><strong>Usually direct sown:</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>Spinach</li>
        <li>Beans</li>
        <li>Carrots</li>
        <li>Radishes</li>
      </ul>

      <p>
        In shorter climates, giving warm crops a controlled indoor start
        increases the likelihood they mature before first frost returns.
        For the planning logic behind this method, see
        <a href="/guides/counting-backward-from-frost-how-seed-timing-works/">Counting Backward From Frost</a>.
      </p>
    </section>